Instructions for building dgrib (GRIB to RALPH converter)


1. First compile rams_wgrib.c with you favorite C compiler. 
      For example, using Linux:

   gcc -o rams_wgrib rams_wgrib.c

   rams_wgrib is virtually unchanged from the standard wgrib, except
      a small change was made to allow 'dump' to write to stdout.
      Make sure that rams_wgrib is in your path if not running
      from the compiled directory.

2. Edit the Makefile for your system and run make. An executable 
   called "grib2olam" should be created.


For running dgrib:

1. Type grib2olam -? for help:

 Usage: grib2olam [-f namelist_file] [-g gribfile] [-t yyyymmddhh] [-h hh]
        namelist file name defaults to DGRIB_IN
       -t : data time to process - yyyymmddhh
       -h : forecast hour - hh
 
            If c_date or c_hr set to '99999999',
            the date/hour of the first record
            in the grib file will be used.
 
       Command line arguments will override the namelist!



2. Edit DGRIB_IN (or a namelist file by any other name) to choose 
   the variables from the grib file you want to process.
   
   For the NCEP Reanalysis files, the 3D variables are typically:
   
   nvar3d=5, var3d='UGRD','VGRD','TMP','HGT','RH',

   For some formats of ECMWF files:
   
   nvar3d=5, var3d='U','V','T','Z','R',
   
   2-dimensional variables are not necessary at this time for RAMS.
   
   If you are uncertain which variables are on the file, use:
   
   wgrib -s "grib-file-name"   or:
   rams_wgrib -s "grib-file-name"
   
   
3. Run "grib2olam". If you use the command line arguments, these will override 
   the settings in the namelist.


Various assumptions are made:

- If a variable begins with an "R" it is assumed to be relative humidity 
  in percent, thus is converted to fraction.
  
- All pressure levels that are found for the first "var3d(1)" are used.

- The variables are written to the Ralph file in the order they are specified. 
  Make sure they are in the order of "u,v,t,z,r" if using for RAMS.
  
  
